ğŸš€ How to Connect to a GPU Server and Download Large Datasets (Simple Guide)

This guide explains how I connect to a university GPU server and download large datasets safely.
No advanced Linux knowledge needed.

ğŸ§  Big Picture (ELI5 version)

Think of the GPU server like a very powerful computer in another building.

What we do:

Connect to that computer

Create our own workspace

Download big datasets directly on the server (much faster)

Organize everything neatly

1ï¸âƒ£ Connect to the GPU Server
Step 1: Connect to VPN

Open the Cisco VPN desktop app

Connect to the university VPN
(This makes your laptop â€œinsideâ€ the campus network)

Step 2: Open terminal on your laptop

Windows â†’ Command Prompt or PowerShell

Step 3: Connect to GPU machine
ssh <GPU_USERNAME>@<GPU_SERVER_ADDRESS>


âœ… After login, you will see something like:

username@server-name:~$


This means you are now inside the GPU server.

2ï¸âƒ£ Create Your Personal Workspace

We never work in shared folders.

mkdir -p ~/my_workspace
cd ~/my_workspace


Create clean subfolders:

mkdir data projects runs logs


ğŸ“ Folder meaning (simple):

data/ â†’ datasets

projects/ â†’ code

runs/ â†’ model outputs

logs/ â†’ training logs

3ï¸âƒ£ Check GPU Availability

Before using GPUs, always check:

nvidia-smi


This shows:

How many GPUs exist

Which ones are busy

How much memory is free

4ï¸âƒ£ Why We Download Data on the Server (Important)

âŒ Uploading from laptop â†’ slow, breaks often
âœ… Downloading on server â†’ fast, stable

So we always download large datasets directly on the server.

5ï¸âƒ£ Download Datasets from Synapse (Simple & Safe)
Step 1: Go to dataset folder
cd ~/my_workspace/data/<DATASET_NAME>


Example:

cd ~/my_workspace/data/GLI

Step 2: Set access token (hidden)
export SYN_TOKEN="YOUR_SYNapse_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN"


ğŸ” Token is:

Stored only in memory

Removed later

Never committed to Git

Step 3: Download files (one by one)
synapse -p "$SYN_TOKEN" get <synID>.1 --downloadLocation .


Example:

synapse -p "$SYN_TOKEN" get syn12345678.1 --downloadLocation .


Repeat for each file.

Step 4: Verify download
ls -lh


You should see:

File name

File size (GBs for large datasets)

Step 5: Remove token from memory (important)
unset SYN_TOKEN

6ï¸âƒ£ Repeat for Other Datasets

Same steps for:

GLI

MEN

MET

PED

SSA

Only change:

cd ~/my_workspace/data/<FOLDER_NAME>


Everything else stays the same.

7ï¸âƒ£ Final Sanity Check (All Data)
du -sh ~/my_workspace/data/*


This confirms:

Which datasets exist

Rough sizes

Nothing missing

ğŸ§¸ Ultra-Simple Summary (Child Version)

Turn on VPN

Open terminal

Connect to big computer

